00:00:01.689 --> 00:00:04.540
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Today it is my pleasure
to introduce our speaker to you.

00:00:04.540 --> 00:00:11.360
Born right here in the Bay Area, Michael Ellsberg
is a renowned expert in entrepreneurialism,

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:15.860
career development, and education, whose work
has been featured in the New York Times, the

00:00:15.860 --> 00:00:21.410
Wall Street Journal, CNN, and Good Morning
America to name just a few.

00:00:21.410 --> 00:00:26.090
Michael is author of the incredibly popular
"The Power of Eye Contact: Your Secret for

00:00:26.090 --> 00:00:31.539
Success in Business, Love, and Life," a book
that provides simple tools for improving relationships

00:00:31.539 --> 00:00:34.020
throughout all areas of your life.

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:38.710
He also writes the Need to Know blog for Forbes
dot com, which is full of even more valuable

00:00:38.710 --> 00:00:40.379
tips for personal success.

00:00:40.379 --> 00:00:45.269
His new book, "The Education of Millionaires:
It's Not What You Think and It's Not Too Late,"

00:00:45.269 --> 00:00:49.910
will be released on September 29th, but we
were lucky to get a few pre-release copies

00:00:49.910 --> 00:00:52.190
over here if you're interested.

00:00:52.190 --> 00:00:57.760
While the workplace today often places heavy
importance on a person's alma mater, for his

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:01.749
new book, Michael spent the past year and
a half interviewing some of the world’s

00:01:01.749 --> 00:01:06.010
most successful individuals who did not obtain
a college degree.

00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:10.960
Instead, these individuals were self-taught
and learned the skills they needed for success

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:13.790
through their experiences in the real world.

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:18.690
In his talk today, Get Rich and Invest In
Your Own Human Capital, Michael will explain

00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:23.510
how to make the most fast-acting, direct,
high-impact investments in your own human

00:01:23.510 --> 00:01:28.890
capital and career success based on what he
learned from these masters of self-education

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:31.600
and from his own personal experience.

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:36.230
And with that, please join me in welcoming
Michael Ellsberg.

00:01:36.230 --> 00:01:38.760
[applause]

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:51.550
&gt;&gt;Michael Ellsberg: So, what I plan to do
in the next 45 minutes is to radically alter

00:01:51.550 --> 00:01:55.310
the way you all think about the concept of
investing.

00:01:55.310 --> 00:02:03.940
Now, you are all highly accomplished engineers,
managers, executives, professionals in Silicon

00:02:03.940 --> 00:02:06.850
Valley, the heart of innovation in America.

00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:10.470
You all work for a legendary company in the
history of capitalism.

00:02:10.470 --> 00:02:16.070
So, for me to stand up here and say that in
45 minutes I might alter the way you think

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:21.300
about a concept as fundamental as investing
is a tall order, but that is what I'm gonna

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:23.260
aim for today.

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:29.510
So, I'm not here to talk about stocks, bonds,
real estate, 401Ks.

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:32.569
You've all heard those kinds of lectures before.

00:02:32.569 --> 00:02:35.870
You all know the rap about that kind of investing.

00:02:35.870 --> 00:02:39.850
The type of investing I wanna talk about is
one you've probably heard less about 'cause

00:02:39.850 --> 00:02:41.870
it's discussed a lot less.

00:02:41.870 --> 00:02:43.890
But I think it's very, very important.

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:47.819
And that is investing in your own human capital.

00:02:47.819 --> 00:02:51.230
And the title of the talk today is "Get Rich
Investing In Your Own Human Capital."

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:55.280
If you haven't guessed already, its slightly
tongue in cheek title, I wanted to poke a

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:59.030
bit of fun at all those books about the other
kind of investing.

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:01.069
Get rich investing in real estate!

00:03:01.069 --> 00:03:08.810
But in all seriousness, I do think that investing
in your human capital can potentially much

00:03:08.810 --> 00:03:13.370
more lucrative than all those other kinds
of more traditional investments.

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:19.560
It's possibly much more safe, which is something
that we're all interested in now given the

00:03:19.560 --> 00:03:22.480
craziness of the markets in the last several
years.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:29.330
And it also can be possibly more rewarding
and more fitting in with the fabric of your

00:03:29.330 --> 00:03:31.010
career and your sense of meaning.

00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:33.069
So, that's what we're gonna be talking about.

00:03:33.069 --> 00:03:36.280
And I'm gonna start with a pretty uncontroversial
statement.

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:39.020
We'll get to a bit on controversy later.

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:41.170
But let's start with uncontroversy.

00:03:41.170 --> 00:03:47.320
Most economists, most career development professionals,
will agree that spending your time, spending

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:51.570
your money, investing in human capital is
a really good investment.

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:55.470
So, you're not gonna find many people who
disagree with that statement.

00:03:55.470 --> 00:04:02.870
But almost all the discussion around that
concept focuses on investments in formal credentials

00:04:02.870 --> 00:04:05.239
and formal higher education.

00:04:05.239 --> 00:04:07.300
And those can be very powerful investments.

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:13.599
And I know that Google, as a corporate culture,
highly values educational attainment, educational

00:04:13.599 --> 00:04:16.500
investments in its employees and its recruits.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:19.650
And you've all probably in this room made
a lot of those investments.

00:04:19.650 --> 00:04:24.130
And those can be very powerful, very worthwhile
investments.

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:27.160
But almost all the discussion centers around
those.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:31.760
And there's a whole world of investments that
I've been exploring over the last several

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:38.910
years talking to very successful people who
didn't go that path, who boot-strapped their

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:41.150
human development, their human capital.

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:45.870
And so, if you think of formal education,
it might be thought of as almost a venture

00:04:45.870 --> 00:04:52.800
capital model of investing in your human capital
in that there's often a lot of financing involved,

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:59.810
a lot of effort in money up-front; sixteen,
eighteen years to get through elementary school,

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:02.880
undergraduate, more years for graduate education.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:08.870
And then, after all this investment, all this
potentially financing in debt, then you get

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:11.570
some benefit afterwards.

00:05:11.570 --> 00:05:17.010
And what I want to talk to you about today
is styles investing in yourself that can just

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:20.910
be put into action right now with not a lot
of expenditure of money.

00:05:20.910 --> 00:05:25.100
You don't have to leave this wonderful campus
where there's all this free food available

00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:27.680
that I've already been enjoying.

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:30.180
And you don't have to take time off from your
career.

00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:32.470
You don't have to go into student debt.

00:05:32.470 --> 00:05:34.490
It's available to you right now.

00:05:34.490 --> 00:05:40.380
So, these might be thought of as more of a
boot-strapping model of human capital development.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:41.450
Or, lean.

00:05:41.450 --> 00:05:46.680
Lean is a very hot word now in the investing,
entrepreneurial world.

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:50.400
Or, you could think of it as a guerilla-style
of investing.

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:55.220
So, that's what we're gonna be talking about
for the next 40 minutes or so.

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:57.460
Now, before I dive in, who am I?

00:05:57.460 --> 00:06:01.800
Why the heck do I have any credibility at
all to be talking with you about this today?

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:05.780
So, I'm a professional author, book author.

00:06:05.780 --> 00:06:08.620
This is my second book that's been published.

00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:09.961
There's a few before that weren't published.

00:06:09.961 --> 00:06:12.330
I won't talk about those.

00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:15.080
But this one is coming out in a couple weeks
from Penguin.

00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:18.580
It's called "The Education of Millionaires."

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:22.090
And you're actually some of the first people
to hear about it or even see it.

00:06:22.090 --> 00:06:26.110
I just saw this book like two days ago for
the first time.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:34.070
And what I did is I got very interested in
this question of how can you develop your

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:38.600
talents outside of the normal ways that we
hear about developing your talents, going

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:39.600
back to school.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:45.310
And to explore that question, I decided to
interview some of the most successful people

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:48.419
on the planet who don't have college degrees.

00:06:48.419 --> 00:06:50.270
And I went around the country.

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:55.860
I talked to about 35 millionaires, self-made
millionaires, entrepreneurs, who didn't finish

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:58.300
college, about four billionaires.

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:00.430
Some of them are pretty famous.

00:07:00.430 --> 00:07:03.860
Dustin Moskovitz, co-founder of Facebook.

00:07:03.860 --> 00:07:08.400
I talked to Sean Parker, founding president,
who by the way, if you've seen the movie "The

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:12.930
Social Network," I think he is totally different
than Justin Timberlake.

00:07:12.930 --> 00:07:18.810
They did him a disservice in that movie after
hanging out with him for a couple hours and

00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:21.820
picking his brain about this stuff.

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:25.420
I interviewed Matt Mullenweg, who is the founder
of Wordpress.

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:27.620
I run my own personal blog on that.

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:30.680
Probably a lot of you are familiar with Wordpress.

00:07:30.680 --> 00:07:35.180
Outside of the tech world, I spoke John Paul
DeJoria.

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:37.850
He's the co-founder of John Paul Mitchell
Systems.

00:07:37.850 --> 00:07:40.930
He was homeless at two points in his life
early.

00:07:40.930 --> 00:07:47.150
Lived out of a car with his son and was at
one point collecting soda bottles to make

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:49.669
sure that he had enough money to feed his
son.

00:07:49.669 --> 00:07:54.270
And he went in business with a hairdresser
called Paul Mitchell.

00:07:54.270 --> 00:07:59.259
They invested, I think, like 700 dollars in
creating their first formula.

00:07:59.259 --> 00:08:04.000
They went salon to salon, built it into a
multi-billion dollar business.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.680
And he's been on the Forbes 400 forever now.

00:08:08.680 --> 00:08:16.080
And another person on that list I interviewed
was Phillip Ruffin, who started out building

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:17.080
a hamburger ch--.

00:08:17.080 --> 00:08:18.330
Not even a chain, a stand.

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:20.380
A hamburger stand in college.

00:08:20.380 --> 00:08:23.410
He eventually decided to drop out to build
that.

00:08:23.410 --> 00:08:25.550
Built it up quite successfully.

00:08:25.550 --> 00:08:27.240
Just kept building businesses.

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:31.780
Now he owns Treasure Island Resort and Casino
on Las Vegas strip.

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:35.919
So, a bunch of famous people.

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:39.960
I also just interviewed people you probably
haven't heard of, but who are just doing really,

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:42.320
really interesting cutting edge things.

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:47.550
The inspiration for my book actually was my
wife, Jenna, who's here in the front with

00:08:47.550 --> 00:08:48.550
my mother.

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:51.850
And Jenna is a successful entrepreneur.

00:08:51.850 --> 00:08:57.690
She has a thriving weight loss coaching practice
and wellness center in Manhattan.

00:08:57.690 --> 00:08:59.529
And she dropped out of college in Australia.

00:08:59.529 --> 00:09:03.730
So, she was the inspiration for me getting
excited about this topic.

00:09:03.730 --> 00:09:07.251
For the record, I did graduate--Brown class
of '99.

00:09:07.251 --> 00:09:12.680
So, I'm not an example of the people that
I write about.

00:09:12.680 --> 00:09:15.640
[pause]

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:23.320
So, we're gonna get into some really specific
takeaways that I wanna give you in this next

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:24.370
40-odd minutes.

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:29.850
You're gonna come away with some really specific
things you can implement for your career success.

00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:35.720
Before we dive into that, I wanna get a kind
of more Google Earth view of the issue and

00:09:35.720 --> 00:09:40.430
then we'll zoom in more specifically towards
the end of the talk.

00:09:40.430 --> 00:09:42.660
And we'll also have plenty of time for questions.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:45.990
So, the Google Earth view.

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:51.130
In my write-up for this talk, which you may
have seen or not, I'm not sure, I start out

00:09:51.130 --> 00:09:55.860
with a comparison about two different types
of people.

00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:58.450
Take a billionaire executive.

00:09:58.450 --> 00:10:04.190
You probably know of a few here in this company,
or just someone who is at the top of their

00:10:04.190 --> 00:10:05.980
game in the corporate world.

00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:11.200
And then you take someone who's earning minimum
wage, which is around seven fifty an hour

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:13.160
these days.

00:10:13.160 --> 00:10:16.550
These two people don't have very much in common
professionally.

00:10:16.550 --> 00:10:19.700
They pretty much couldn't be more opposite
professionally.

00:10:19.700 --> 00:10:23.800
Except, they have one really, really important
thing in common.

00:10:23.800 --> 00:10:29.070
Can anyone guess what that one thing they
have in common is?

00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:31.830
They both have 24 hours in the day.

00:10:31.830 --> 00:10:33.390
I don't care how much money you have.

00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:36.240
There are ways you can use money to leverage
your time.

00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:40.330
But I don't care how much money you have,
even if you owned all the stock of Google

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:46.340
on IPO day and cash it out that day, all that
money could not buy you a 25th hour of the

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:47.340
day.

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:49.560
So, we're all working with 24 hours.

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:55.269
So then the interesting question becomes,
what distinguishes these two kinds of workers

00:10:55.269 --> 00:10:57.670
who have the same amount of time to work with?

00:10:57.670 --> 00:11:00.410
Why is one earning so much more than the other?

00:11:00.410 --> 00:11:01.930
And it's quite dramatic.

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:07.260
The average executive compensation for CEO
of a major corporation is around ten million

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:13.680
dollars in both salary and stock options and
benefits.

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:17.800
I know that Larry and Sergey were at one point
taking one dollar, so they're not the best

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:18.800
example here.

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:23.140
But your average CEO of a large corporation
is around ten million dollars.

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:29.790
They don't get paid hourly, but if you break
that down say, 80 hour weeks, 50 weeks a year,

00:11:29.790 --> 00:11:33.279
you're looking at somewhere around three thousand
dollars an hour the market is valuating their

00:11:33.279 --> 00:11:40.080
time versus someone whose minimum wage pouring
coffee kinda thing is getting valued at seven

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:41.640
fifty.

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:44.330
And they're both putting in roughly the same
amount of time each day.

00:11:44.330 --> 00:11:46.310
So, what is the difference between them?

00:11:46.310 --> 00:11:51.810
Well, economists, when they look at who's
earning what and why people are earning more,

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:58.100
they have this concept called "productivity,"
the productivity of someone's work.

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:00.459
And productivity is a pretty simple function.

00:12:00.459 --> 00:12:05.570
It's just a function of labor, the time you're
putting in, mixed with capital.

00:12:05.570 --> 00:12:07.720
So, you take the same amount of labor.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:09.300
You mix it with more capital.

00:12:09.300 --> 00:12:12.490
And you get more productivity, more compensation.

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:19.320
So you think of someone who's earning minimum
wage, their capital is a mop and very basic

00:12:19.320 --> 00:12:22.620
level of training to clean what they're cleaning.

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:24.149
It's a low amount of capital.

00:12:24.149 --> 00:12:29.920
They're mixing their time and they get low
results financial-wise, whereas very highly

00:12:29.920 --> 00:12:35.890
compensated executive is putting in roughly
the same hours, but they are mixing those

00:12:35.890 --> 00:12:40.080
hours with an enormous amount of capital for
each minute they're putting in.

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:42.920
It's being mixed with an enormous amount of
capital.

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:45.630
They have, of course, a human capital.

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:51.160
They have their training, formal education,
and their informal training, all their experience

00:12:51.160 --> 00:12:52.160
on the job.

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:57.060
They have a rolodex, which is a form of human
capital, or it might be called social capital.

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:59.740
Then they have all the capital of the company.

00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:05.779
They have executive teams that can put their
vision, execute on their vision.

00:13:05.779 --> 00:13:08.089
They have all the financial resources accompanied.

00:13:08.089 --> 00:13:14.000
So each minute is being mixed with a lot of
capital and that's why more value gets created

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:15.529
out of each minute.

00:13:15.529 --> 00:13:18.240
So, what I wanna do today--.

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:23.620
You all have a lot of human capital already
in your expertise, your education, of course

00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:31.070
your experience, but I wanna give some really
guerilla-style boot-strapped ways you can

00:13:31.070 --> 00:13:36.160
start adding even more to your human capital
so that each minute of your time, each hour

00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:41.269
you spend here is mixed with more capital
and therefore, more valuable.

00:13:41.269 --> 00:13:46.660
And that your career will develop that much
faster, your compensation, your earnings will

00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:48.270
develop that much faster.

00:13:48.270 --> 00:13:55.800
So, I'm gonna talk about four main types of
lean, or boot-strapped, human capital that

00:13:55.800 --> 00:13:56.860
we can all add to.

00:13:56.860 --> 00:14:01.080
And the first one I'm gonna talk about is
sales.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:02.810
And that might sound a little bit crazy.

00:14:02.810 --> 00:14:06.329
I'll bet a lot of you in the audience are
engineers.

00:14:06.329 --> 00:14:12.899
You may not ever in your career get in a position
of formally selling something in the context

00:14:12.899 --> 00:14:13.899
of the business.

00:14:13.899 --> 00:14:16.769
Maybe some of you do, but my guess is probably
most of you don't.

00:14:16.769 --> 00:14:22.089
So, why would I be standing up here telling
you that learning about sales is a valuable

00:14:22.089 --> 00:14:24.290
way to add to your human capital?

00:14:24.290 --> 00:14:30.420
Well, even if you're not selling a product
for money, all of us, all of you, are working

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:33.600
in a knowledge economy, a knowledge society
here.

00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:40.080
And we'd like in a certain sense, you're getting
paid for your creativity and your ideas.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:45.889
And we'd like to think that the best ideas
win, but we know in office politics, in just

00:14:45.889 --> 00:14:49.800
the way things work, that isn't always the
case.

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:56.480
The ideas that win are the best ideas multiplied
by the best persuasion, the best influence,

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:59.019
the best sales, if you will, of those ideas.

00:14:59.019 --> 00:15:04.589
So, formal education, which we've all had,
I've had, teaches us about the ideas.

00:15:04.589 --> 00:15:10.779
It's a pure idea environment where there's
this very high premium on coming up with brilliant

00:15:10.779 --> 00:15:11.779
ideas.

00:15:11.779 --> 00:15:16.490
But the thing that you don't tend to learn
in a formal environment is how to pitch and

00:15:16.490 --> 00:15:21.660
sell and persuade those ideas to real world
teams in the real world.

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:27.850
And someone I interviewed for this book actually
once went through the entire course catalog

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:35.740
of Harvard's, Stanford, and Wharton Business
Schools and was looking for courses in sales.

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:40.550
And there was not a single course in sales
in the entire MBA catalogs of those three

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:44.850
most prestigious business MBA programs.

00:15:44.850 --> 00:15:48.820
There was one course in sales force management,
which is very different from sales.

00:15:48.820 --> 00:15:53.370
Now, if you talk to the people I interviewed
in my book, these self-made millionaires,

00:15:53.370 --> 00:15:58.160
self-made billionaires, successful entrepreneurs,
if you talk to them about what was behind

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:05.980
their success, they are almost all very, very
passionate about the concept of sales, both

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:10.890
traditional sales in the sense of selling
