I mean, there's a sign right there you can
check out about a meditation group.

00:22:49.909 --> 00:22:56.390
There's a specific kind of investing in your
attention span and the quality of your attention

00:22:56.390 --> 00:23:00.429
that I wanna talk about that's very near and
dear to my heart.

00:23:00.429 --> 00:23:04.299
I had a pretty serious problem with this issue
in my 20s.

00:23:04.299 --> 00:23:06.279
I'm 34.

00:23:06.279 --> 00:23:11.909
Four years ago, on the eve of my 30th birthday,
I was suicidal.

00:23:11.909 --> 00:23:17.369
And I had struggled throughout my 20s with
Bipolar II, which a pretty serious mental

00:23:17.369 --> 00:23:20.989
illness that involves really strong mood swings.

00:23:20.989 --> 00:23:23.480
So, my attention was really either--.

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:24.480
It was one of two things.

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:29.049
It was either super jacked up, where I was
like this and could barely contain myself,

00:23:29.049 --> 00:23:34.919
which was surprisingly actually hard to be
productive 'cause my mind was just so jacked

00:23:34.919 --> 00:23:35.919
up.

00:23:35.919 --> 00:23:41.639
Or, I was in bed and I could barely get out
of bed and pull the covers off of me.

00:23:41.639 --> 00:23:45.450
So, neither of those was very conducive to
good work.

00:23:45.450 --> 00:23:51.549
And if you think this stuff about attention
is airy-fairy and New Age, it really isn't.

00:23:51.549 --> 00:23:55.489
It has a very direct correlation with your
earnings.

00:23:55.489 --> 00:24:02.779
So, in the darkest moments of that period,
I was working as a freelancer and I earned

00:24:02.779 --> 00:24:07.059
in my lowest year eight thousand dollars in
one year.

00:24:07.059 --> 00:24:12.460
'Cause I just wasn't able to bring quality
attention to my hours in a day.

00:24:12.460 --> 00:24:14.710
And it showed in my pocketbook.

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:16.879
And the way I got out of this, it was a long
story.

00:24:16.879 --> 00:24:19.389
I actually wrote an article about it on Forbes.

00:24:19.389 --> 00:24:24.149
If you Google my name and Bipolar II, I have
a very detailed article about it.

00:24:24.149 --> 00:24:27.940
But essentially, I got of this through better
nutritional and eating habits.

00:24:27.940 --> 00:24:31.960
And I went through a whole gauntlet of doctors,
psychiatrists.

00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:34.389
I was on all kinds of drugs.

00:24:34.389 --> 00:24:42.519
And eventually, I came to a doctor who knew
that there were nutritional components to

00:24:42.519 --> 00:24:44.450
attention and to mood.

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:48.899
And he told, specifically with these mood
swings, that sugar was a really big issue

00:24:48.899 --> 00:24:50.120
and blood sugars issues.

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:57.929
And he told me to get off caffeine, alcohol,
and refined sugar, which I was all of them

00:24:57.929 --> 00:25:00.159
consuming in rather high quantities.

00:25:00.159 --> 00:25:03.149
I resisted this advice for quite a while.

00:25:03.149 --> 00:25:07.729
I basically told him to F-off and that I didn't
wanna live without those things.

00:25:07.729 --> 00:25:10.509
Eventually, it got really bad, as I mentioned.

00:25:10.509 --> 00:25:12.940
I was literally on the verge of suicide.

00:25:12.940 --> 00:25:14.880
I was like, "I need to make a change."

00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:17.529
I implemented what this doctor told me.

00:25:17.529 --> 00:25:21.549
And within two weeks, my life had radically
transformed.

00:25:21.549 --> 00:25:27.229
And so, you don't need to be in the brinks
of that level of darkness to have this effective.

00:25:27.229 --> 00:25:32.299
Google is on the forefront, literally the
forefront, and I'm not saying this to flatter

00:25:32.299 --> 00:25:33.299
you.

00:25:33.299 --> 00:25:41.289
It's actually true, of paying attention to
people, worker's nutrition as a component

00:25:41.289 --> 00:25:44.869
of their value in the company and the attention
they're bringing.

00:25:44.869 --> 00:25:49.110
And Google has gotten deservedly a ton of
great press about the healthy food that's

00:25:49.110 --> 00:25:52.409
available to you in the cafe and all of that.

00:25:52.409 --> 00:25:53.639
But we can always do better.

00:25:53.639 --> 00:25:54.960
We can always learn more.

00:25:54.960 --> 00:26:00.379
There's a very high leverage way to increase
the value of each minute you're bringing to

00:26:00.379 --> 00:26:03.929
your day, is to get this part of your life
handled.

00:26:03.929 --> 00:26:07.389
To get your nutrition, your health, really
handled.

00:26:07.389 --> 00:26:13.840
And probably all of us could tick off a list
of the basic things you need to do to be healthy.

00:26:13.840 --> 00:26:19.440
We all know it's basically eat more fresh
fruits and vegetables, cut down on refined

00:26:19.440 --> 00:26:24.241
sugars, cut down on alcohol consumption and
caffeine consumption, get more exercise, get

00:26:24.241 --> 00:26:25.241
better sleep.

00:26:25.241 --> 00:26:26.489
All of us know these things.

00:26:26.489 --> 00:26:28.070
But really the difference--.

00:26:28.070 --> 00:26:31.970
The difference is whether we implement them
or not.

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:38.359
So, again, this is in some ways one of the
fallacies of formal training and education

00:26:38.359 --> 00:26:43.229
is that it's really about like what you know
and do you know things intellectually and

00:26:43.229 --> 00:26:47.099
can you tick them off on a test.

00:26:47.099 --> 00:26:50.219
But what you know is only part of the issue.

00:26:50.219 --> 00:26:52.090
Really, it's what you put into practice.

00:26:52.090 --> 00:26:56.379
And that is actually in some ways the more
challenging part.

00:26:56.379 --> 00:26:58.929
And you really have to train at these things.

00:26:58.929 --> 00:27:01.490
I think there's an analogy to training like
an athlete.

00:27:01.490 --> 00:27:08.779
You actually have to train your taste buds,
your senses to respond to healthier eating.

00:27:08.779 --> 00:27:10.980
And it is a training process.

