00:29:14.330 --> 00:29:18.029
And that is what I call "overcoming emotional
liabilities."

00:29:18.029 --> 00:29:20.549
Overcoming emotional liabilities.

00:29:20.549 --> 00:29:24.039
And I have a very technical definition of
emotional liabilities.

00:29:24.039 --> 00:29:27.450
You might want to take notes on this technical
definition.

00:29:27.450 --> 00:29:33.070
I define an emotional liability as any emotional
issue you haven't dealt with that could come

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:35.690
back and bite you in the ass.

00:29:35.690 --> 00:29:36.879
And we all have these.

00:29:36.879 --> 00:29:37.879
All of us.

00:29:37.879 --> 00:29:38.960
I definitely, definitely have these.

00:29:38.960 --> 00:29:41.899
All of us in this room have emotional liabilities.

00:29:41.899 --> 00:29:45.019
Usually, we're not aware of them.

00:29:45.019 --> 00:29:48.340
Another way you might think of them is blind
spots.

00:29:48.340 --> 00:29:51.351
So, everyone else is aware of them.

00:29:51.351 --> 00:29:55.129
I assure you your team is aware of your emotional
liabilities.

00:29:55.129 --> 00:29:56.820
You're the only one who isn't.

00:29:56.820 --> 00:29:58.220
Same thing goes for me.

00:29:58.220 --> 00:30:00.539
One that I struggle with a lot--.

00:30:00.539 --> 00:30:05.809
So, there's several kinds that I'll talk about
that are very common in the work world.

00:30:05.809 --> 00:30:10.839
One that I personally struggle with a lot
is defensiveness, which is essentially being

00:30:10.839 --> 00:30:15.070
totally unopen to any kind of feedback around
your improvement.

00:30:15.070 --> 00:30:16.429
My wife is laughing.

00:30:16.429 --> 00:30:19.879
She is the one who is the mirror to my blind
spots.

00:30:19.879 --> 00:30:27.950
So, she'll say something very reasonable,
very normal, wifely criticism of a husband.

00:30:27.950 --> 00:30:32.249
And I'll get extremely defensive and I'll
deny it and I'll start criticizing her right

00:30:32.249 --> 00:30:33.249
back.

00:30:33.249 --> 00:30:34.249
And she's very patient.

00:30:34.249 --> 00:30:38.549
I'm very lucky to have such a patient wife,
who will patiently and compassionately say,

00:30:38.549 --> 00:30:41.249
"Honey, you're doing that defensiveness thing
again."

00:30:41.249 --> 00:30:44.589
And she's gotta actually point it out to me
'cause when you're in the grips of it, you're

00:30:44.589 --> 00:30:46.009
actually not aware of it.

00:30:46.009 --> 00:30:50.279
You're possessed by this and you don't see
it, but everyone else sees it.

00:30:50.279 --> 00:30:52.029
So, defensiveness.

00:30:52.029 --> 00:30:57.669
Another one that's extremely common in the
work world is what I "victim mentality."

00:30:57.669 --> 00:31:00.100
And I have a whole chapter about that in here.

00:31:00.100 --> 00:31:04.459
I call it the "entrepreneurial mindset versus
the employee mindset."

00:31:04.459 --> 00:31:05.459
And these are mindsets.

00:31:05.459 --> 00:31:08.589
This is not about whether you're actually
an entrepreneur or an employee.

00:31:08.589 --> 00:31:10.309
It's about mindset.

00:31:10.309 --> 00:31:14.299
And one thing that I noticed about all the
people I interviewed is they seem to have

00:31:14.299 --> 00:31:15.469
a mindset in common.

00:31:15.469 --> 00:31:18.320
And I call that mindset the "entrepreneurial
mindset."

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:22.359
And it's very relevant if you're an employee
also.

00:31:22.359 --> 00:31:29.979
The essence of that mindset is a complete
absence of any kind of victim mentality and

00:31:29.979 --> 00:31:34.839
a sense that these people are creating the
results around them.

00:31:34.839 --> 00:31:36.609
They are the cause of the results.

00:31:36.609 --> 00:31:40.919
So, if you're in a victim mentality, everyone
else is the cause of your results, of your

00:31:40.919 --> 00:31:42.009
bad results.

00:31:42.009 --> 00:31:46.029
So, if your team doesn't do well on a project,
"Well, it's my team members.

00:31:46.029 --> 00:31:50.989
They didn't get that piece of programming,
that piece of code in on time."

00:31:50.989 --> 00:31:53.249
All those kinds of excuses that we always
hear.

00:31:53.249 --> 00:31:59.529
So, you're not really the cause of the bad
things in your life, but the problem with

00:31:59.529 --> 00:32:01.589
that is that it throws the baby out with the
bath water.

00:32:01.589 --> 00:32:07.639
If you're adopting this mentality where everything
else is the cause, then you're not really

00:32:07.639 --> 00:32:09.709
the cause of good things in your life, either.

00:32:09.709 --> 00:32:13.989
And so, the people I interviewed have a very
different mindset around this.

00:32:13.989 --> 00:32:16.789
And I think it stems from them being entrepreneurs.

00:32:16.789 --> 00:32:24.190
Where, if you're an entrepreneur and one of
your employee’s screws up, maybe some entrepreneurs

00:32:24.190 --> 00:32:25.899
say, "Oh, well the employee is terrible.

00:32:25.899 --> 00:32:27.249
It's their fault.

00:32:27.249 --> 00:32:28.499
That's why we messed up."

00:32:28.499 --> 00:32:30.469
But those kinds of entrepreneurs don't last
very long.

00:32:30.469 --> 00:32:33.039
The ones that are successful say, "OK, this
is my fault.

00:32:33.039 --> 00:32:34.129
I created this.

00:32:34.129 --> 00:32:37.639
Either I made a bad hiring decision, in which
case I need to fix that.

00:32:37.639 --> 00:32:43.519
Or, I didn't provide the leadership necessary
to have that employee do the right thing.

00:32:43.519 --> 00:32:44.690
So, I'm in control.

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:46.019
I'm in the driver's seat.

00:32:46.019 --> 00:32:47.619
I'm creating my reality."

00:32:47.619 --> 00:32:53.669
There's a lot of cheesy stuff out there about
this issue, the law of attraction and "you

00:32:53.669 --> 00:32:54.999
create your own reality."

00:32:54.999 --> 00:33:00.229
I think for a lot of things that gets overblown
and overhyped.

00:33:00.229 --> 00:33:06.940
And you can fairly have skepticism about some
of the more extreme New Age ways that this

00:33:06.940 --> 00:33:10.109
gets expressed in like that movie "The Secret."

00:33:10.109 --> 00:33:18.099
But just on a basic level, overcoming this
emotional liability of "I'm a victim," "other

00:33:18.099 --> 00:33:22.619
people are screwing me over in my career,"
"if just that one employee, if just that one

00:33:22.619 --> 00:33:27.679
boss did something different than I'd get
the results I want," that's an emotional liability.

00:33:27.679 --> 00:33:35.440
And learning to overcome that is a very, very
powerful way to invest in your own human capital.

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:38.719
So, if you think about the most successful--.

00:33:38.719 --> 00:33:46.159
Think about the best leader you can imagine,
either a boss you've had or just an idealization

00:33:46.159 --> 00:33:47.679
of your perfect boss/leader.

00:33:47.679 --> 00:33:55.740
So, this person is highly inspiring, highly
motivating, makes you wanna work for her,

00:33:55.740 --> 00:34:01.769
makes you want to bring out your best to perform
for the vision she's setting out, is giving

00:34:01.769 --> 00:34:07.070
you really hard-hitting solid feedback, but
done in a very compassionate way that's not

00:34:07.070 --> 00:34:10.419
aimed at cutting you down, but rather in helping
you grow.

00:34:10.419 --> 00:34:13.649
So, you think about the most inspiring leader
like that.

00:34:13.649 --> 00:34:17.849
And we've all probably had one or two in some
context or another.

00:34:17.849 --> 00:34:24.169
That person has overcome a lot of their emotional
liabilities 'cause we've all got them from

00:34:24.169 --> 00:34:25.169
childhood.

00:34:25.169 --> 00:34:26.230
My mother is here, also.

00:34:26.230 --> 00:34:31.470
I had a very happy childhood, but just from
normal growing up stuff, we've all got this

00:34:31.470 --> 00:34:37.030
baggage that we carry around and if we don't
learn to let go of the baggage, it will come

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:38.609
back to bite us in the ass.

00:34:38.609 --> 00:34:41.579
And it will affect, this is not airy-fairy
New Age stuff.

00:34:41.579 --> 00:34:44.820
it will affect your bottom line.

00:34:44.820 --> 00:34:53.290
And so, again on the theme of specific takeaways,
on this one, emotional liabilities is very

00:34:53.290 --> 00:34:56.230
hard to do just on your own because as we
said, they're blind spots.

00:34:56.230 --> 00:34:58.260
So, you need feedback.

00:34:58.260 --> 00:35:01.150
And I'm a very big believer in executive coaching.

00:35:01.150 --> 00:35:06.250
I'm almost like a religious convert to executive
coaching.

00:35:06.250 --> 00:35:09.110
It's transformed my own life, my own earning
power.

00:35:09.110 --> 00:35:15.000
I mentioned in the darkest days of my professional
life, I earned eight thousand dollars in one

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:16.000
year.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:20.869
That was just about four or five years ago
until I finally got my health issues taken

00:35:20.869 --> 00:35:25.319
care of, which is the second kind of human
capital we talk about.

00:35:25.319 --> 00:35:29.910
And then I was in a place to start, once I
got my health taken care of, to start focusing

00:35:29.910 --> 00:35:30.910
on my money.

00:35:30.910 --> 00:35:31.910
And I said, "You know what?

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:35.190
I can't be in this place any longer.

00:35:35.190 --> 00:35:37.340
I've got to get my money handled.

00:35:37.340 --> 00:35:39.839
And I'm not gonna attract--.

00:35:39.839 --> 00:35:45.349
No woman that I want to spend my life with
is gonna wanna be married to such a financial

00:35:45.349 --> 00:35:46.360
basket case."

00:35:46.360 --> 00:35:49.740
And this is before I met Jena and I really
had my vision.

00:35:49.740 --> 00:35:54.190
I needed to get this handled to meet the kind
of partner that I wanted to have in my life.

00:35:54.190 --> 00:36:00.849
So, I invested and it was literally a financial
investment in really high-quality coaching.

00:36:00.849 --> 00:36:05.450
And there's all kinds of workshops out there,
coaching you can get.

00:36:05.450 --> 00:36:08.770
Again, there's enormous amount of BS out there.

00:36:08.770 --> 00:36:15.140
I would say, I'm probably gonna piss some
people off for listening to this on the video,

00:36:15.140 --> 00:36:20.440
but I would say 80% of coaches I've come across
are pretty messed up in their own life and

00:36:20.440 --> 00:36:25.380
they're using coaching as a way to sort out
their own life by coaching other people.

00:36:25.380 --> 00:36:29.450
That's a really, really common meme that you'll
see out there.

00:36:29.450 --> 00:36:33.230
So, you gotta find the people who aren't like
that, who actually have their stuff already

00:36:33.230 --> 00:36:34.230
handled.

00:36:34.230 --> 00:36:39.849
And who can help you get your emotional liabilities
handled.

00:36:39.849 --> 00:36:42.730
What's the best way to find them?

00:36:42.730 --> 00:36:45.819
Referrals is always the best way I think.

00:36:45.819 --> 00:36:47.690
Find people who've got this stuff handled.

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:49.660
Find people who are where you wanna be.

00:36:49.660 --> 00:36:54.589
Find, whether in this company or elsewhere
in the Valley, find people who are where you

00:36:54.589 --> 00:36:59.339
wanna be and ask who they learned from.

00:36:59.339 --> 00:37:00.690
What books did they read?

00:37:00.690 --> 00:37:01.799
What teachers did they have?

00:37:01.799 --> 00:37:03.070
What mentors did they have?

00:37:03.070 --> 00:37:07.520
It's possible that those people teach workshops,
teach classes.

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:12.039
I'll make two recommendations right here if
you're looking for specific recommendations.

00:37:12.039 --> 00:37:13.099
I have no--.

00:37:13.099 --> 00:37:15.140
I'm not affiliated with these people.

00:37:15.140 --> 00:37:20.710
I have no benefit from recommending them,
but one is actually a former Googler, Jenny

00:37:20.710 --> 00:37:26.570
Blake, who used to organize this Authors@Google
series.

00:37:26.570 --> 00:37:32.089
And she was an executive coach here at Google
and she decided to go out and do it full-time

00:37:32.089 --> 00:37:33.089
herself.

00:37:33.089 --> 00:37:34.490
She's great.

00:37:34.490 --> 00:37:36.490
She's helped me a lot.

00:37:36.490 --> 00:37:37.700
She's a friend now.

00:37:37.700 --> 00:37:39.981
I actually pay an executive coach also.

00:37:39.981 --> 00:37:43.779
So, there's a mix of informal and formal.

00:37:43.779 --> 00:37:46.890
So, you can find mentors, which is a form
of coaching.

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:52.430
But I really do believe in investing with
your wallet and paying for some executive

00:37:52.430 --> 00:37:53.430
coaching.

00:37:53.430 --> 00:37:55.920
I pay for an executive coach.

00:37:55.920 --> 00:37:59.079
He's a guy called Peter Shallard.

00:37:59.079 --> 00:38:00.079
S-H-A-L-L-A-R-D.

00:38:00.079 --> 00:38:02.849
He goes by the moniker, "The Shrink for Entrepreneurs."

00:38:02.849 --> 00:38:08.539
And I think we're all, whether employees or
not, we all live in an entrepreneurial environment.

00:38:08.539 --> 00:38:12.410
We all need some kind of shrink quote/unquote.

00:38:12.410 --> 00:38:17.040
And so, go out and find one that works for
you and make that investment.

00:38:17.040 --> 00:38:19.529
A good executive coach--.

00:38:19.529 --> 00:38:23.849
The going rate for a really good one who knows
what they're doing is about a thousand dollars

00:38:23.849 --> 00:38:25.029
a month.

00:38:25.029 --> 00:38:32.050
And that may sound like a lot, but compare
that, for example, to going back and getting

00:38:32.050 --> 00:38:33.319
a master’s degree.

00:38:33.319 --> 00:38:39.630
That could be 50 thousand dollars a year for
a good program plus forgone earnings.

00:38:39.630 --> 00:38:43.630
That could be another 50 to 100 thousand dollars
a year in forgone earnings.

00:38:43.630 --> 00:38:45.450
Much of that will be put on debt.

00:38:45.450 --> 00:38:48.819
So, there's gonna be interest associated with
the debt.

00:38:48.819 --> 00:38:55.930
So, you're looking at possibly 150 thousand
dollars a year to get that kind of formal

00:38:55.930 --> 00:39:01.070
increase in your human capital, whereas a
really good executive coach might be one-tenth

00:39:01.070 --> 00:39:02.849
of that in a year.

00:39:02.849 --> 00:39:09.329
It's gonna be a form of education, but highly
tailored to your specific needs and your specific

00:39:09.329 --> 00:39:12.230
circumstances.

00:39:12.230 --> 00:39:18.680
And again, this is like a more kind of guerilla
lean style where you don't have to leave your

00:39:18.680 --> 00:39:20.250
job.

00:39:20.250 --> 00:39:25.049
This is done in dialogue with your job, this
kind of education.

00:39:25.049 --> 00:39:30.890
And all the people I talked to in this book
are really, really big believers in the power

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:32.430
of mentorship.

00:39:32.430 --> 00:39:36.650
And since they didn't have formal educations,
they didn't have professors, they had to go

00:39:36.650 --> 00:39:38.540
and find their professors in the world.

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:44.390
So, I have a chapter, the second chapter in
the book, is a step-by-step way to go on how

00:39:44.390 --> 00:39:49.619
to find informal mentors who can help you
with these issues and help us get to that

00:39:49.619 --> 00:39:56.329
higher, more clean level of leadership where
we're not getting triggered and weighed down

00:39:56.329 --> 00:39:57.930
by emotional baggage issues.

00:39:57.930 --> 00:40:04.170
So, that's the third kind of human capital
investment.

00:40:04.170 --> 00:40:11.950
And the last type of human capital that I'm
gonna talk about today is meaning and bringing

00:40:11.950 --> 00:40:14.700
meaning to our careers.

00:40:14.700 --> 00:40:19.900
And I have another pretty serious personal
story around this.

00:40:19.900 --> 00:40:24.309
After dealing with that whole bipolar health
issue, I got out of it.

00:40:24.309 --> 00:40:26.150
I got out alive.

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:30.549
Pretty soon after that, I got diagnosed with
testicular cancer about two and a half years

00:40:30.549 --> 00:40:31.720
ago.

00:40:31.720 --> 00:40:38.060
And knock on wood, I got the surgery four
days after I found out about it.

00:40:38.060 --> 00:40:39.390
I was on the surgery table.

00:40:39.390 --> 00:40:40.430
I got the surgery.

00:40:40.430 --> 00:40:41.730
Everything seems to be OK now.

00:40:41.730 --> 00:40:46.030
So I am a cancer survivor of two and half
years.

00:40:46.030 --> 00:40:52.000
And it's kind of clichéd or cheesy, but there's
something about being diagnosed with a potentially

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:57.250
fatal illness that gives you a permission
slip to really start thinking about these

00:40:57.250 --> 00:40:58.330
big issues.

00:40:58.330 --> 00:41:01.579
Like, what does my life mean?

00:41:01.579 --> 00:41:05.079
What impact do I really want to make here
on the planet?

00:41:05.079 --> 00:41:11.960
And so, I thought about those a lot during
the time of the surgery and after.

00:41:11.960 --> 00:41:16.250
And I just spent a lot of time thinking about
those issues.

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:23.220
And to me, it's actually kind of sad that
it generally takes a life-threatening illness

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:27.940
for us to give ourselves permission to start
thinking about these issues in our life.

00:41:27.940 --> 00:41:34.089
Steve Jobs just stepped down from his incredible
tenure of leadership.

00:41:34.089 --> 00:41:41.210
There's a really beautiful commencement speech
he gave in 2005 at Stanford where he talks

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:46.769
about this and he talks about his cancer diagnosis
and how he started thinking about these big

00:41:46.769 --> 00:41:51.539
picture issues facing death.

00:41:51.539 --> 00:41:57.109
And my hope is that we all in this room don't
have to face those issues for a very long

00:41:57.109 --> 00:42:01.160
time and we all live very, very healthy long
lives.

00:42:01.160 --> 00:42:07.069
But I want us to give ourselves permission
to think about those issues without facing

00:42:07.069 --> 00:42:08.980
mortality and do it now.

00:42:08.980 --> 00:42:13.589
And again, this is not an airy-fairy concept.

00:42:13.589 --> 00:42:17.779
It has direct relevance to your success in
your career.

00:42:17.779 --> 00:42:23.130
So, if you take two people again, same educational
background, same training, same technical

00:42:23.130 --> 00:42:24.130
skills.

00:42:24.130 --> 00:42:28.740
One of them is just showing up for work like,
"Hey, Google's a cool place to work and get

00:42:28.740 --> 00:42:30.150
this free food.

00:42:30.150 --> 00:42:31.740
It sounds cool on my resume."

00:42:31.740 --> 00:42:33.569
And that's their relation to their work.

00:42:33.569 --> 00:42:34.769
Not a lot of meaning.

00:42:34.769 --> 00:42:42.410
And you take someone else who has a very clear
sense of what they want to accomplish on this

00:42:42.410 --> 00:42:47.740
planet, of what impact they want to have made
in their company, in the industry, in the

00:42:47.740 --> 00:42:49.940
world, through their work.

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:52.460
Which one of those two people is gonna be
promoted faster?

00:42:52.460 --> 00:42:55.130
Which one is gonna advance in their career?

00:42:55.130 --> 00:42:57.250
Which one is gonna earn more over their career?

00:42:57.250 --> 00:42:59.050
It's really clear the latter one will.

00:42:59.050 --> 00:43:04.369
So, I'm gonna give you my definition of meaning
and how we can add more to it.

00:43:04.369 --> 00:43:09.970
I'm sure that you did not expect coming at
12 PM at a lunchtime talk to get a definition

00:43:09.970 --> 00:43:15.690
of the meaning of life, but I'm gonna give
you mine right here from a lot of reflection.

00:43:15.690 --> 00:43:19.619
The way I like to think about it is the way
we can add more meaning to our lives and our

00:43:19.619 --> 00:43:28.440
career is making a difference in the lives
of people you care about.

00:43:28.440 --> 00:43:30.940
Making a difference in the people you care
about.

00:43:30.940 --> 00:43:32.460
And there's two components to that.

00:43:32.460 --> 00:43:35.170
Making a difference and the people you care
about.

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:39.190
And both of those components need to be there
for a sense of meaning.

00:43:39.190 --> 00:43:45.269
So, I have two of the most important people
in my life here: my mother, who gave me life.

00:43:45.269 --> 00:43:49.859
My wife, who gives me life every day and inspiration.

00:43:49.859 --> 00:43:54.319
And these are people I deeply, deeply care
about.

00:43:54.319 --> 00:43:57.440
And Jena and I just had our one year wedding
anniversary.

00:43:57.440 --> 00:44:03.190
And a year ago, a little over a year ago,
I was giving her my vows in the wedding and

00:44:03.190 --> 00:44:10.420
I said, "Jena, I vow to you that if you're
ever in danger, if you're ever in harm's way,

00:44:10.420 --> 00:44:12.400
I will sacrifice everything.

00:44:12.400 --> 00:44:17.589
I will sacrifice even my own life to protect
you and to get you out of harm."

00:44:17.589 --> 00:44:23.070
And I meant those words and there's very few
people on the planet I would say those words

00:44:23.070 --> 00:44:26.060
to, but I said them to Jena that day.

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:29.320
And that is a level of meaning that I'm talking
about here.

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:32.960
That's the level of care and we all have that
in our families.

00:44:32.960 --> 00:44:38.560
We all have that with people we love, whether
it's a spouse or significant other, children,

00:44:38.560 --> 00:44:41.220
siblings, parents.

00:44:41.220 --> 00:44:46.030
And so, we get this is in our personal life
that that's what gives us meaning is making

00:44:46.030 --> 00:44:47.030
a difference.

00:44:47.030 --> 00:44:50.849
On that difference point, it's not just caring.

00:44:50.849 --> 00:44:52.089
It's also--.

00:44:52.089 --> 00:44:53.089
This is--.

00:44:53.089 --> 00:44:57.220
Jena is someone I care deeply about and I
know I'm making a difference in her life.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:45:02.750
I know that her life is very different because
I'm in it and we have a relationship.

00:45:02.750 --> 00:45:03.930
And it goes both ways.

00:45:03.930 --> 00:45:09.970
My life is completely different and pretty
much unrecognizable because of Jena's care

00:45:09.970 --> 00:45:12.529
and the difference she's making on me.

00:45:12.529 --> 00:45:14.970
So, it's the caring and the making a difference.

00:45:14.970 --> 00:45:18.579
So, how does this translate into the professional
realm?

00:45:18.579 --> 00:45:24.640
Well, the level of care may or may not be
that intense, but you all work with people.

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:25.740
We like to think--.

00:45:25.740 --> 00:45:32.410
We may think that we're here because of technical
skills, because of training background.

00:45:32.410 --> 00:45:35.519
But nothing gets done without people.

00:45:35.519 --> 00:45:38.300
And you all work on teams.

00:45:38.300 --> 00:45:41.329
And presumably, you care about your teams.

00:45:41.329 --> 00:45:44.440
And there's an analogy here.

00:45:44.440 --> 00:45:50.670
If you interview soldiers about why they fight,
why they put up with these horrendous, hellish

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:55.839
conditions, what keeps them going day after
day on no sleep, risking their life every

00:45:55.839 --> 00:45:56.839
day?

00:45:56.839 --> 00:46:01.930
If you interview people like that about why
they do it, they may say something about the

00:46:01.930 --> 00:46:03.869
cause or the reason they're fighting or their
country.

00:46:03.869 --> 00:46:09.569
But if you really dig deep and read the interviews
with them, almost always they're talking about

00:46:09.569 --> 00:46:14.730
their team mates, their fellow soldiers and
this profound love and care they have for

00:46:14.730 --> 00:46:16.759
the people that on are on their side.

00:46:16.759 --> 00:46:21.450
And it's very elemental thing in our psychology,
this caring for teams.

00:46:21.450 --> 00:46:27.759
So, the more you learn how to get in touch
with why you're here, why you care about what

00:46:27.759 --> 00:46:33.410
you're doing, the people you care about, and
getting really, really inspired by making

00:46:33.410 --> 00:46:39.610
a difference in what they're doing, the more
powerful your career is gonna be, the more

00:46:39.610 --> 00:46:42.730
powerful each minute of your labor, which
is fixed.

00:46:42.730 --> 00:46:44.579
You only have a certain amount of it each
day.

00:46:44.579 --> 00:46:47.609
So we're talking about how to make it the
most effective.

00:46:47.609 --> 00:46:50.839
The more each minute of that labor is gonna
be powerful.

00:46:50.839 --> 00:46:54.770
And there's not really books or things you
can do.

00:46:54.770 --> 00:46:55.770
This is inquiry.

00:46:55.770 --> 00:47:00.160
This is internal inquiry that we all have
to do.

00:47:00.160 --> 00:47:04.910
And it tends to get put aside for other types
of investing.

00:47:04.910 --> 00:47:09.780
So, people, when they think of investing,
they think of stocks, bonds, real estate,

00:47:09.780 --> 00:47:10.780
